    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2014/03/bank-that-claimed-to-solve-bitcoins-security-problem-robbed-shuts-down/?comments=1&amp;post=26360029" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">jxmzsr</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Someone please tell us again how foolproof/secure the bitcoin system is and how impossible it is for them to be stolen.</div><br><br>It's quite difficult to steal them, if you hold them yourselves, securely.  It's empirically rather easy to steal them if you trust some (uninsured) third party with them, who creates a very tempting target for attackers.  There's the whole "Why do you rob banks?" "That's where the money is!" thing going on with "convenient" web wallets &amp; such - they're attacked because they're very profitable to attack.  And, given the amount pulled from most of them, it's well worth burning 0-days to succeed.<br><br>Bitcoin is like gold/silver - if you don't have it in your possession (sole owner of the private key), it's not really yours.
      
    </div>
