  data-post-score="83"
  data-post-negative="-5"
  data-post-positive="88"
  data-post-id="26360099" data-poster-id="32907" id="comment-26360099">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="Syonyk"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=32907&amp;sid=e048854bc138e565d18581a2d2516ebd">Syonyk</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Legatus Legionis</span><a class="subscriber" href="/subscriptions/">et Subscriptor</a>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2014/03/bank-that-claimed-to-solve-bitcoins-security-problem-robbed-shuts-down/?comments=1&post=26360099#comment-26360099" title="2014-03-04T09:39:47-06:00" class="timeago datetime">Tue Mar 04, 2014 9:39 am</a>
        
          <span class="highlight reader-fav">Reader Fav</span>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26360029#p26360029" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">jxmzsr</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Someone please tell us again how foolproof/secure the bitcoin system is and how impossible it is for them to be stolen.</div><br /><br />It's quite difficult to steal them, if you hold them yourselves, securely.  It's empirically rather easy to steal them if you trust some (uninsured) third party with them, who creates a very tempting target for attackers.  There's the whole &quot;Why do you rob banks?&quot; &quot;That's where the money is!&quot; thing going on with &quot;convenient&quot; web wallets &amp; such - they're attacked because they're very profitable to attack.  And, given the amount pulled from most of them, it's well worth burning 0-days to succeed.<br /><br />Bitcoin is like gold/silver - if you don't have it in your possession (sole owner of the private key), it's not really yours.
      
    </div>
    <footer>
      <aside class="vote">
        
