    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26360099#p26360099" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Syonyk</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26360029#p26360029" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">jxmzsr</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Someone please tell us again how foolproof/secure the bitcoin system is and how impossible it is for them to be stolen.</div><br /><br />It's quite difficult to steal them, if you hold them yourselves, securely.  It's empirically rather easy to steal them if you trust some (uninsured) third party with them, who creates a very tempting target for attackers.  There's the whole &quot;Why do you rob banks?&quot; &quot;That's where the money is!&quot; thing going on with &quot;convenient&quot; web wallets &amp; such - they're attacked because they're very profitable to attack.  And, given the amount pulled from most of them, it's well worth burning 0-days to succeed.<br /><br />Bitcoin is like gold/silver - if you don't have it in your possession (sole owner of the private key), it's not really yours.</div><br />Exactly! I don't understand why people hold balances in third-party wallets. Bitcoin's crypto is designed to be secure in a distributed scenario, to make sure you don't have to put your money in centralized locations.<br /><br />(Edited for clarity)
      
        <p class="edited">Last edited by <a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=179807&amp;sid=e048854bc138e565d18581a2d2516ebd">sep332</a> on Tue Mar 04, 2014 10:09 am</p>
      
