    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26360099#p26360099" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Syonyk</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26360029#p26360029" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">jxmzsr</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Someone please tell us again how foolproof/secure the bitcoin system is and how impossible it is for them to be stolen.</div><br /><br />It's quite difficult to steal them, if you hold them yourselves, securely.  It's empirically rather easy to steal them if you trust some (uninsured) third party with them, who creates a very tempting target for attackers.  There's the whole &quot;Why do you rob banks?&quot; &quot;That's where the money is!&quot; thing going on with &quot;convenient&quot; web wallets &amp; such - they're attacked because they're very profitable to attack.  And, given the amount pulled from most of them, it's well worth burning 0-days to succeed.<br /><br />Bitcoin is like gold/silver - if you don't have it in your possession (sole owner of the private key), it's not really yours.</div><br /><br />Exactly.  Putting Bitcoins on these exchanges is like putting them in poorly guarded banks that brag about their security and don't insure your deposits.  Of course, the lack of secure exchanges does limit their usefulness as a replacement currency and will likely prevent them from gaining a mainstream following.
      
    </div>
