<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment contro read"
  data-post-score="8"
  data-post-negative="-71"
  data-post-positive="79"
  data-post-id="26360413" data-poster-id="32907" id="comment-26360413">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="Syonyk"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=32907&amp;sid=e048854bc138e565d18581a2d2516ebd">Syonyk</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Legatus Legionis</span><a class="subscriber" href="/subscriptions/">et Subscriptor</a>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2014/03/bank-that-claimed-to-solve-bitcoins-security-problem-robbed-shuts-down/?comments=1&post=26360413#comment-26360413" title="2014-03-04T10:05:51-06:00" class="timeago datetime">Tue Mar 04, 2014 10:05 am</a>
        
          <span class="highlight controversial">Controversial</span>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26360215#p26360215" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">WDReinhart</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Just the (large, vocal) subset of Bitcoin users who have been insufferable smug pricks about the superiority of Bitcoin to government-issued currencies for the last 3 years.</div><br /><br />If I take a stack of USD $100 bills, and give them to a guy on the street corner who claims he's a &quot;totally legit awesome secure bank&quot; on his cardboard sign, and he runs off with them, does that mean that USD is broken, or that it was stupid to let a random guy hold them for me?<br /><br />If I do the same thing with silver, does that mean silver is broken?  Or does it just mean I'm an idiot?<br /><br />Bitcoin has a lot of advantages over government-issue currencies, which still hold.  But it turns out, like with many other things, letting untrustworthy people hold your currency/commodity/value for you is a really bad idea.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26360217#p26360217" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">dmsilev</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">As far as I can tell, there are three reasons why people use Bitcoins:<br />1) Philosophical reasons. Wanting a distributed currency independent of central banks, desire for anonymity, etc.<br />..<br />The people in group (1) are finding out good and hard just why things like the FDIC exist.</div><br /><br />Are you sure?  You assert that they are, but I'm willing to bet if you actually /asked/ a few of those people what their thoughts were, the first thing out of their mouth wouldn't be, &quot;Oh, wow, yeah, we need FDIC insurance for Bitcoin.&quot;  I don't know that I've talked to anyone who uses Bitcoin for philosophical/economic reasons who immediately jumps to &quot;WOW NEED INSURANCE!&quot; when something like this happens - it's understood that it's a higher risk way of storing value, but they feel the advantages outweigh the disadvantages.  Also, people who are pretty hardcore about distributed currencies tend not to keep a huge amount of value in centralized services.<br /><br />It's also likely that a lot of those people feel that FDIC insurance has been a major contributor to banks gambling with their deposited funds because, hey, if they screw up and lose it, the government will bail the customers out!  You have what should be savings banks playing super risky investment games, because there's no penalty if they fail!<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26360259#p26360259" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">bglick4</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Of course, the lack of secure exchanges does limit their usefulness as a replacement currency and will likely prevent them from gaining a mainstream following.</div><br /><br />There's a difference between an exchange and a bank.  If one is using an exchange (say, MtGox) as an exchange, and pulling currencies out as soon as they're exchanged, the risk is quite low.  If one is using them as a long term bank... not a great idea.<br /><br />It's been shown, quite clearly, that most third party services claiming to securely store bitcoin aren't capable of doing so for the long term.  If you are involved in bitcoin and continue to use said services, the risk is your decision to make.  Personally, I think if you have significant bitcoin holdings on a computer/USB key/paper in a safe/etc you don't control, you're kind of stupid.  But it's your decision to make.<br /><br />//EDIT: Oh, come on.  If you're going to downvote me, at least have the courage to reply with what you object to.
      
        <p class="edited">Last edited by <a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=32907&amp;sid=e048854bc138e565d18581a2d2516ebd">Syonyk</a> on Tue Mar 04, 2014 10:16 am</p>
      
    </div>
