<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment neutral read"
  data-post-score="6"
  data-post-negative="-3"
  data-post-positive="9"
  data-post-id="26360567" data-poster-id="16224" id="comment-26360567">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="Nimdok"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=16224&amp;sid=e048854bc138e565d18581a2d2516ebd">Nimdok</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Scholae Palatinae</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2014/03/bank-that-claimed-to-solve-bitcoins-security-problem-robbed-shuts-down/?comments=1&post=26360567#comment-26360567" title="2014-03-04T10:20:15-06:00" class="timeago datetime">Tue Mar 04, 2014 10:20 am</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26360005#p26360005" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Ulf</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">People whine and whine and whine about regulations, but there's a reason why they exist.</div><br /><br />It's a shame the Bitcoin threads always devolve into the pro/anti regulation arguments, because there are many types of regulations, and I honestly believe to some extent Bitcoin is inherently not possible to regulate.<br /><br />Bitcoin is in fact already subject to one form of regulation: anti-money laundering laws.  This is why in order to buy Bitcoins you must submit a huge pile of paperwork and personal information to the exchanges.<br /><br />On US Federal Reserve Notes, in addition to regulations on money laundering, there are regulations on money creation.  The Fed monitors loan issuance at banks, which is the primary source of money creation, and it can also print money to buy assets to boost the economy (or so they say).<br /><br />As mathematically-inclined folks, we would all agree it's not possible to regulate the &quot;money creation&quot; aspect of Bitcoin, aye?<br /><br />So the only remaining form of regulation that Bitcoin could even possibly subjected to is in the form of security.  I would be interested in hearing what sort of laws folks believe would somehow make Bitcoin banks more secure.  I personally would avoid keeping enough Bitcoins to even want to put in a bank.  There are just too many risks involved in safely and privately storing a list of numbers.
      
    </div>
    <footer>
